keywords elys savan rakuen cistern works
---
Elys Savan is remembered in Rakuen as the architect-symbol of cooperative waterworks built before the Ashfall collapse.
She designed and oversaw construction of the cistern network that allowed Rakuen's predecessor settlement to survive extended dry periods.
Her method was collaborative: she integrated Deltari hydraulic mapping, Kethari aquifer knowledge, and human construction labor into a single engineering program.
The cistern works she planned required cross-community agreement at a scale no single institution controlled. She brokered that agreement personally.
The Ashfall disrupted the supply chains her systems depended on and ultimately forced modifications she had not anticipated in her original plans.
The works survived. Many survive in functional form today, supplemented by later construction but still relying on her original channel alignments.
Rakuen's Garden Ledger treats her as a founding civic figure rather than a historical engineer: her name attaches to cooperative infrastructure as a category.
A project described as Savan-method in Rakuen means: multi-community contribution, shared maintenance obligation, long design horizon, no single proprietor.
Her personal biography is poorly documented. There is no birth record, city of origin, or lineage file in any surviving archive.
What survives is the infrastructure and the method. Rakuen considers this the appropriate memorial for someone who built for collective use, not personal legacy.
The Ashborn communities near Rakuen maintain a separate tradition: they credit Savan with negotiating their inclusion in the cistern works over institutional objection.

