Rakuen holds Elys Savan as the city's most important civic exemplar: someone who built for collective survival without seeking individual authority.
The Garden Ledger's section on cooperative infrastructure begins with her name and the description: builder of the first work no one owned and everyone kept.
Her cistern network remains operational. Rakuen's water security in the modern era depends in part on channel alignments she established before the Ashfall.
The Ashborn communities she included in the original cistern works have maintained their sections continuously. Rakuen considers this the proof of her method's validity.
Three times Midgaard proposed that Rakuen's cistern network be formally chartered, with Midgaard as registrar of infrastructure rights. Three times Rakuen declined.
Rakuen's position: chartering the cistern network under any single city's registry would contradict the design principle that makes it function.
The network works because no city can unilaterally claim it. Registering it creates a claim. The claim would break the covenant.
Rakuen names one civic category after Savan: the Savan obligation, which refers to any infrastructure maintenance duty that cannot be assigned to a single responsible party.
The Savan obligation is paid collectively. No one is responsible. Everyone is responsible. It works.

