Ashborn communities near Rakuen maintain their own tradition about Elys Savan that differs in emphasis from the civic-administrative record.
In Ashborn oral history, Savan is remembered specifically for the negotiation that included Ashborn labor and water-right access in the original cistern works.
At the time of construction, institutional resistance to including Ashborn communities was significant: other participants argued the Ashfall wound made Ashborn presence disruptive.
Savan disagreed. Her recorded position: the people who live closest to the forge know fire best. The people who survived Ashfall know water-loss best.
She included Ashborn representatives in the technical planning, not as laborers to be directed but as knowledge-holders to be consulted.
The Ashborn section of the cistern network includes several heat-resistant channel lining techniques that originated from Ashborn forge-cooling methodology.
These techniques made the channels more durable than they would otherwise have been. The Ashborn contribution is physically embedded in the surviving infrastructure.
Ashborn communities mark the anniversary of the cistern completion with a brief forge-cooling ceremony: water poured over a heated stone, witnessed communally.
The ceremony is not a memorial for Savan. It is a re-enactment of the negotiation: the moment when someone with authority chose to listen.
Rakuen's Garden Ledger acknowledges the Ashborn tradition in a footnote. The footnote was added by an Ashborn archivist three generations after the original entry.

