Deltari involvement in the Savan cistern works is documented in Reed Law references that predate any other surviving record of the project.
Deltari hydraulic mapping of the Rakuen-adjacent channel system provided the foundational survey data Savan used for her channel alignments.
Reed Law — Deltari legal tradition governing water-flow rights, seasonal adjustment obligations, and channel maintenance duties — was integrated directly into the original cistern covenant.
This integration means the cistern works operate under two overlapping legal traditions: Rakuen civic infrastructure law and Deltari Reed Law.
When maintenance disputes arise, they are adjudicated first under Reed Law principles and then under Rakuen civic procedure.
Deltari in Rakuen treat this as the correct ordering: water-law precedes land-law because water existed before the land was inhabited.
The Savan-method principle — no single proprietor — is consistent with Reed Law's rejection of permanent water ownership: water moves, and ownership of flow is temporary custody.
Deltari measure the cistern network's health in flow-rate terms rather than volume-capacity terms: a healthy cistern system moves correctly, not merely holds enough.
By Deltari measurement, Savan's original channel alignments are still the most flow-efficient sections of the network after all subsequent modifications.
